<taxonomicName box="[151,366,730,756]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="524" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucidus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,366,730,756]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="524">Polyergus lucidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,794,927]" pageId="23" pageNumber="524">
This group comprises six, mostly eastern North American species, deep red to orange-red, often with conspicuously darker appendages, and very reduced pubescence and pilosity of the gastral dorsum. All parasitize members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[341,505,866,891]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="524" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidefulva">
<emphasis box="[341,505,866,891]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="524">F. pallidefulva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. As a group these have relatively long appendages compared to the more pubescent, western North American species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[720,945,902,927]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="524" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviceps">
<emphasis box="[720,945,902,927]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="524">Polyergus breviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex.
</paragraph>
